<TITLE> 4 Indian militants get 17 years </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Sylhet, Apr 29 (bdnews24.com)--A Sylhet court on Thursday handed down 17 years in prison to each of the four Indian militants. The BDR captured the four Indian citizens on Jul 15, 2005 while they were infiltrating into Bangladesh territory with huge firearms and grenades. Sylhet's first additional district and sessions judge and special tribunal-2 acting judge Jalaluddin Ahmmad delivered the verdict on Robin, 46, Milon, 19, Abar, 26, and Easter, 38, Shillong of India. They are referred to as members of an Indian militant group in the case documents. The case stated that border guards of 21 Rifles Battalion captured the four along Khara-Bala border near Kanaighat Upazila on July 15, 2005. BDR members seized AK-56 assault rifles, 9mm pistol, grenades and some Indian and Bangladeshi currency from them. BDR nayed subedar Amir Khasru filed a case with Kanaighat police on July 15, 2005 and handed them over to police. Later they were sent to Sylhet jail showing them arrested under Special Powers Act. Kanaighat police sub-inspector Abdur Razzaque and Jamaluddin Bhuiyan completed investigation in one month and pressed charges in the court on Aug 14, 2005. The court framed the charges on Nov 10 the same year and took statement from 21 witnesses out of 27. bd
